  "text": "## Root Cause Analysis: Envoy `overflow` Reset Reason\n\n### 1. The `overflow` string definition\n\nThe string `\"overflow\"` in the error message `upstream connect error or disconnect/reset before headers. reset reason: overflow` is produced by `Utility::resetReasonToString()` in **envoy--v1.31.2** at `source/common/http/utility.cc` (line 1031). This function maps `Http::StreamResetReason::Overflow` (defined in `envoy/http/stream_reset_handler.h`) to the string `\"overflow\"`.\n\nThe full error message is assembled in `Filter::onUpstreamReset()` in `source/common/router/router.cc` (line 1415-1420) using `absl::StrCat(\"upstream connect error or disconnect/reset before headers. \", ..., \"reset reason: \", Http::Utility::resetReasonToString(reset_reason), ...)`.\n\n### 2. Connection pool overflow trigger points\n\nThere are two distinct overflow conditions in the connection pool implementation, both in **envoy--v1.31.2** under `source/common/conn_pool/conn_pool_base.cc`:\n\n**a) Pending requests overflow** (`newStreamImpl`, line 282-287): When a new stream arrives and there are no ready connections, Envoy checks `host_->cluster().resourceManager(priority_).pendingRequests().canCreate()`. If the pending request queue is at capacity (controlled by `max_pending_requests` circuit breaker threshold, default 1024), it calls `onPoolFailure(..., ConnectionPool::PoolFailureReason::Overflow, ...)` and increments `upstream_rq_pending_overflow_`.\n\n**b) Max requests (active streams) overflow** (`attachStreamToClient`, line 175-180): When attaching a stream to a ready client, Envoy checks `host_->cluster().resourceManager(priority_).requests().canCreate()`. If the active request limit is exceeded (controlled by `max_requests`, default 1024), it similarly fires `onPoolFailure` with `PoolFailureReason::Overflow` and increments `upstream_rq_pending_overflow_`.\n\n**c) Max connections overflow** (`tryCreateNewConnection`, line 135-139): When creating a new connection, `host_->canCreateConnection(priority_)` checks both per-host connection limits and the cluster-wide `max_connections` circuit breaker. If exceeded, `upstream_cx_overflow_` is incremented. The connection may still be created if the pool has no existing connections (to avoid starvation), but is rate-limited.\n\nThe HTTP-layer pool (`source/common/http/conn_pool_base.cc`, `HttpConnPoolImplBase`) inherits all this logic from `ConnPoolImplBase` and adds HTTP-specific stream reset handling in `MultiplexedActiveClientBase::onStreamReset()`.\n\nThe `PoolFailureReason::Overflow` is translated to `Http::StreamResetReason::Overflow` in `UpstreamRequest::onPoolFailure()` (`source/common/router/upstream_request.cc`, line 569-570), which then triggers `onResetStream()` → `Filter::onUpstreamReset()` in the router.\n\n### 3. Circuit breaker configuration protobuf\n\nThe circuit breaker thresholds controlling `max_connections` and `max_pending_requests` are defined in **data-plane-api--84e84367** at:\n- `envoy/config/cluster/v3/circuit_breaker.proto` (current v3 API, `CircuitBreakers.Thresholds` message)\n- `envoy/api/v2/cluster/circuit_breaker.proto` (frozen v2 API)\n\nThe `CircuitBreakers.Thresholds` message contains:\n- `max_connections` (field 2): maximum upstream connections per priority (default 1024)\n- `max_pending_requests` (field 3): maximum queued pending requests (default 1024)\n- `max_requests` (field 4): maximum parallel active requests (default 1024)\n\nThese are loaded into `ResourceManagerImpl` via `ClusterInfoImpl::ResourceManagers::load()` in `source/common/upstream/upstream_impl.cc`, which reads the `circuit_breakers().thresholds()` from the cluster config proto and instantiates `ResourceManagerImpl` with the parsed values. The `ResourceManagerImpl` (in `source/common/upstream/resource_manager_impl.h`) uses `ManagedResourceImpl` (backed by `BasicResourceLimitImpl`) to track current usage and expose `canCreate()` checks that the connection pool queries at runtime."
